  1. Each chick should have twelve weight measurements. Use the dplyr package to identify how many measurements are there for each chick. Extract a subset of the data for all chicks with complete information, name the data set complete, and print the first 3 rows. (Hint: you might want to use mutate to introduce a helper variable consisting of the number of observations)
complete <- ChickWeight %>%
  group_by(Chick) %>%
  mutate(total=n()) %>%
  filter(total == 12)

  1. In the complete data set introduce a new variable that measures the current weight difference compared to day 0. Name this variable weightgain and print the first 3 rows of the new data frame.
dat4 <- ChickWeight %>%
  group_by(Chick) %>%
  mutate(weightgain = weight - weight[Time == 0])

head(dat4, 3)
  1. Use {ggplot2} to create side-by-side boxplots of weightgain by Diet for day 21. Change the order of the categories in the Diet variable such that the boxplots are ordered by median weightgain, and the lower limit of the y axis should be 0. Describe the relationship in 2-3 sentences.
dat5 <- dat4 %>%
  filter(Time== 21)
  
ggplot(dat5, aes(x= Diet, y=weightgain)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  labs(title="Weight Game on Day 21 by Diet Type ", 
       x = "Diet Tip", 
       y = "Weight Gain") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

ggplot(dat5, aes(x = reorder(Diet, weightgain, FUN=median), y = weightgain)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

From the graph it looks like chicks on diet 1 gained the least weight, and chicks on diet 3 gained the most, followed by chicks on diet 4 then on diet 2.

  1. Which chick gained the most weight and which gained the least weight?
ggplot(dat5, aes(x=reorder(Chick, -weightgain), weight=weightgain)) + geom_bar() +

dat5 %>% ungroup %>%

            maxChick = Chick[which(weightgain == max(weightgain))], 
            min = min(weightgain), 
            minChick = Chick[which(weightgain == min(weightgain))])

  1. For the chicks with the least and the most weight at time 0, plot their growth trajectories over time.
min_max <- dat4 %>% ungroup %>%
  filter(Time == 0) %>%
  filter(weight== max(weight) | weight==min(weight))

lilChicks <- min_max %>%
  filter(weight == 39) %>%
  select(Chick)

lil <- as.numeric(lilChicks$Chick)


bigChicks <- min_max %>%
  filter(weight == 43) %>%
  select(Chick) 

big <- as.numeric(bigChicks$Chick)

dat4 %>% 
  filter(Chick %in% lil) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Time, y=weight, color=Chick)) + geom_smooth(method="lm")+ labs(title="Weight Trajectory of Small Chicks ", 
       x = "Chick Number", 
       y = "Weight") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

dat4 %>%

       x = "Time",

8. Add to the previous plot the average growth trajectory for all chicks (calculated as the mean weight for each chick at each time). How do the trajectories compare?

dat8 <- dat4 %>% ungroup %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  mutate(averageWeight = mean(weight))

dat8big <- dat8 %>%
  filter(Chick %in% big)

ggplot() + 
  geom_smooth(data=dat8big, aes(x=Time, y=weight,color=Chick), method ="lm") +
  geom_smooth(data=dat8big, aes(x=Time, y=averageWeight), method ="lm", color="Black")+
  labs(title="Weight Trajectory of Big Chicks with Average", 
       x = "Time", 
       y = "Weight") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) 

dat8lil <- dat8 %>%
  filter(Chick %in% lil)

ggplot() + 
  geom_smooth(data=dat8lil, aes(x=Time, y=weight,color=Chick), method ="lm") +
  geom_smooth(data=dat8lil, aes(x=Time, y=averageWeight), method ="lm", color="Black")+
  labs(title="Weight Trajectory of Small Chicks with Average", 
       x = "Time", 
       y = "Weight") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

The weight trajectory of small chicks has the average line right in the middle, so they do about the same. The weight trajectory of big chicks are lower than average, which means they arent growing as quickly as average.

  1. What else do you find interesting in the dataset? Show your exploratory analysis.
dat9finished <- ChickWeight %>%
  group_by(Chick) %>%
  mutate(finished=n()) %>%
  mutate(finished = ifelse(finished== 12, "Finished", "Died" )) %>%
  filter(finished == "Finished") %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  mutate(averageWeight = mean(weight))

dat9died <- ChickWeight %>%
  group_by(Chick) %>%
  mutate(finished=n()) %>%
  mutate(finished = ifelse(finished== 12, "Finished", "Died" )) %>%
  filter(finished == "Died") %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  mutate(averageWeight = mean(weight))

ggplot() + 
  geom_smooth(data=dat9finished, aes(x=Time, y=averageWeight), method ="lm", color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(data=dat9died, aes(x=Time, y=averageWeight), method ="lm", color = "black")+
  labs(title="Weight Trajectory Finished vs Died Chicks", 
       x = "Time", 
       y = "Weight") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

I wondered if the chicks that didnt finish the expierement (those who didnt have 12 total weigh ins) differed from those that did. I assumed that because they didnt finish they may have died in development, so I hypothesized that they would have lower weight gain than those who finished the experiment.

From my graph it looks like on average chicks that died grew slower than chicks that survived.
